collectionDetail.name: Creative Dates
collectionDetail.introduction: There’s an art to making happy memories!

experiences.introduction: Who says dates can’t be sweeter? You and your date can learn how to make wagashi, a traditional Japanese sweet, at ABC Cooking Studio. Each class is maxed at four people so you have plenty of support.
experiences.name: ABC Cooking Studio - Central

experiences.introduction: Who says dates can’t be sweeter? You and your date can learn how to make wagashi, a traditional Japanese sweet, at ABC Cooking Studio. Each class is maxed at four people so you have plenty of support.
experiences.name: ABC Cooking Studio - Tsim Sha Tsui

experiences.introduction: Who says dates can’t be sweeter? You and your date can learn how to make wagashi, a traditional Japanese sweet, at ABC Cooking Studio. Each class is maxed at four people so you have plenty of support.
experiences.name: ABC Cooking Studio - Taikoo Shing

experiences.introduction: Whether you and your partner are beginners or experienced in creating art, try Art Loft’s freestyle painting jam. Each session lasts for 2 hours. All art materials provided!
experiences.name: Art Loft

experiences.introduction: Take the time off and create art together with your significant other here at Art Roof Top. Its workshops for adults include life drawing, painting portrait, still life, plein air, and more.
experiences.name: Art Roof Top

experiences.introduction: If you and your date are into arts, head over to Artjammning and let your creativity flow! With high-quality canvasses and free-flow acrylics, you won't run out of ideas.
experiences.name: Artjamming

experiences.introduction: Attend a fun art class at Banana Art Club with your date. Here, art instructions are customised for all ages and abilities. The best part? You can learn together anywhere that’s convenient for you.
experiences.name: Banana Art Club

experiences.introduction: A date isn't complete without food, so spice it up through a memorable culinary experience with BiteUnite. From baking floral cookies and mooncakes to cooking Thai cuisine, BiteUnite has it all!
experiences.name: BiteUnite

experiences.introduction: Learn calligraphy at Bonart Workshops and find yourself and your date exchanging beautifully penned love notes later on! Bonart’s copperplate calligraphy workshops include a starter kit.
experiences.name: Bonart Workshops

experiences.introduction: Learn art while enjoying a 270-degree view of Hong Kong’s streets at Choco L'ART Studio. You and your date can bring your own food and drinks free of charge. Sounds like a perfect date.
experiences.name: Choco L'ART Studio

experiences.introduction: PERMANENTLY CLOSED
experiences.name: Fungus Workshop

experiences.introduction: Creating a couple cup isn't a bad idea, so head over to Glazden for a cup making experience! Here, you'll learn about glass blowing and work with patterns and colours to design your own cup.
experiences.name: Glazden

experiences.introduction: Add a fun twist to your date night by learning pottery at Half Corner Studio. Here, beginners can learn clay preparation and hand-building techniques. Regular and floating classes are available.
experiences.name: Half Corner Studio

experiences.introduction: Impress your significant other by making plum blossom-shaped or goldfish-shaped dumplings learned from Hong Kong New Oriental Culinary Art. The school also offers baking and other cooking classes.
experiences.name: Hong Kong New Oriental Culinary Art

experiences.introduction: What's sweeter than bringing your date to Lazy Baking Studio to craft confections together? Here, you will be guided through baking, layering, creaming, and adding finishing touches.
experiences.name: Lazy Baking Studio

experiences.introduction: Learning hands-on Chinese cuisine at Martha Sherpa's Cooking Classes can be an incredible bonding experience for couples. The school also teaches how to cook vegetarian, Thai, and other dishes.
experiences.name: Martha Sherpa's Cooking Classes

experiences.introduction: Nothing more special than something that's handmade with love. At Motto, you will learn how to make leather wallets, belts, handbags, and more. Bring your date too and make this a bonding!
experiences.name: Motto

experiences.introduction: Try something new with your date this weekend by attending Studio 83’s acrylic and oil class. If you need a space for art creation, the studio has DIY painting sessions available.
experiences.name: Studio 83

experiences.introduction: Immerse in a memorable creative glassmaking experience at Studio Glass. Here, you can learn how to make ornaments, utensils, and other gifts. A perfect way to create your first gift made with glass!
experiences.name: Studio Glass

experiences.introduction: Bake up a little romance by bringing your date at The Little Kitchen Cookery Studio to learn how to create Instagrammable desserts and cakes. You can also learn other savoury dishes here upon request.
experiences.name: The Little Kitchen Cookery Studio

experiences.introduction: Give your date night a different spin by attending Useless Studio’s pottery classes. The studio also offers wheel throwing, ceramic art courses, and other pottery sessions.
experiences.name: Useless Studio

experiences.introduction: Going to a date but you have no one to look after your pets at home? Bring them to Quarry Bay Promenade Pet Garden. There's a park near this 1.8km-waterfront, perfect for strolling with your date!
experiences.name: Quarry Bay Promenade Pet Garden

collectionDetail.name: Hong Kong Heritage
collectionDetail.introduction: Explore the historic wonders of Hong Kong!

experiences.introduction: Walk down 170 Yee Kuk Street and get taken back in time with the verandah-type tong lau or tenement found here. The ground floor used to be a frame-maker’s shop while the floors above were residences.
experiences.name: 170 Yee Kuk Street

experiences.introduction: The Jade Market has been in Yau Ma Tei since 1984 after being first built in Guangzhou Street. Developed in the early 1950s by migrated jade merchants, this market is where you can find a huge selection of jade accessories.
experiences.name: Jade Market

experiences.introduction: Kowloon City Walled Park used to be a lawless zone crowded with around 33,000 residents. Demolished in 1993, the walled city was converted into a landscaped park years later.
experiences.name: Kowloon City Walled Park

experiences.introduction: Man Mo Temple is a historic gem dedicated to worshipping Kwan Tai (Martial God) and King-Emperor Man Cheong, the temple still retains its traditional structures even after renovations.
experiences.name: Man Mo Temple

experiences.introduction: Nam Cheong Pawnshop is today’s reminder of the pawnshop industry that once fueled the city’s economy. This shop still carries the symbol of good fortune arriving — an upside-down bat holding a coin.
experiences.name: Nam Cheong Pawnshop

experiences.introduction: Built during the Qing dynasty, Sam Tung Uk used to be a Hakka walled village featuring symmetrical structures. Today, it’s a historical monument with a museum that is open to the public.
experiences.name: Sam Tung Uk Museum

experiences.introduction: Shing Mun War Tunnels is a heritage trail filled with trenches and tunnels from World War II. Here, you can find the remnants of a defensive line built during the war for New Territories and Kowloon.
experiences.name: Shing Mun War Tunnels

experiences.introduction: If you’re in Hong Kong, visit St. John’s Cathedral, Far East’s oldest Anglican Church that survived World War 2. Beside it is the Memorial Cross dedicated to the soldiers killed during the war.
experiences.name: St. John's Cathedral

experiences.introduction: Tai Kwun is Hong Kong’s Centre for Heritage and Arts that used to be a site for 16 historic buildings composed of 3 declared monuments. It has educational exhibitions and programmes you can join in.
experiences.name: Tai Kwun

experiences.introduction: Marvel at the sight of more than 12,000 miniature Buddha statues at Ten Thousand Buddhas Monastery. Let the view of Buddhas with different expressions entertain you as you go towards the main temple.
experiences.name: Ten Thousand Buddhas Monastery

experiences.introduction: The Blue House by the Stone Nullah Lane is hard to miss. It's flanked by the Orange and Yellow Houses. These three Lingnan-style residential buildings were built in the 192s.
experiences.name: The Blue House

experiences.introduction: Drop by the Po Lin Monastery on Lantau Island to catch a glimpse of Tian Tian or The Big Buddha. This 34-metre tall bronze statue, symbolising harmony between man and nature, is a tranquil sight.
experiences.name: Tian Tian Buddha (Big Buddha)

experiences.introduction: The Tung Lung Chau Rock Carving features a prehistoric carving that might be around 3, years old. At 1.8 by 2.4 metres, it is the largest carving found in the Hong Kong region.
experiences.name: Tung Lung Chau Rock Carving

experiences.introduction: The Edwardian architectural style of the Western Market makes it stand out in Des Voeux Road Central. Recognised as the city's oldest market building, it is now converted into a shopping centre.
experiences.name: Western Market

experiences.introduction: The Police Married Quarters (PMQ) was built in 1951 as a residence for married police staff and their families. In 21, this building was converted into a hub to serve the creative industries.
experiences.name: PMQ

experiences.introduction: Built in the 192s, The Peninsula Hong Kong became a prominent accommodation for dignitaries while in the East. This hotel had been the site of the British's surrender of Hong Kong to Japan.
experiences.name: The Peninsula Hong Kong

collectionDetail.name: Insta Worthy
collectionDetail.introduction: We did it for the gram.

experiences.introduction: K11 MUSEA is a museum of inspiration filled with immersive experiences in art, retail, and more. Snap photos of those endemic plants at Nature Discovery Park as well as the scenes at Donut Playhouse!
experiences.name: K11 Musea

experiences.introduction: Taking The Peak hike will reward you with a photo op with Victoria Harbour and HK's skyscrapers as backdrops. The hike itself is easy and you'll even see children and the elderly along the trail.
experiences.name: The Peak

experiences.introduction: Choi Hung Estate’s pastel rainbow-coloured offers an Insta-worthy backdrop for your pictures. Find a good spot by the building’s basketball court for your shots!
experiences.name: Choi Hung Estate

experiences.introduction: Show your creativity when you snap a shot at the Lok Wah South Estate Car Park. Find that perfect angle where the background seems like a descending circle, and let your subject pose near the centre.
experiences.name: Lok Wah South Estate Car Park

experiences.introduction: A grungy, symmetrical backdrop awaits you at Nam Shan Estate Playground which is located on the roof of a wet market. Come evening and you'll find this place with spot-on lighting to boost your shot.
experiences.name: Nam Shan Estate Playground

experiences.introduction: Lai Tak Tsuen is an estate known for its helical spring-like interior structure that’s ideal for snapping optical illusion-style shots. The building has 27 floors with 486 units.
experiences.name: Lai Tak Tsuen

experiences.introduction: Snap those perfect “lookup” shots at Ping Shek Estate. Standing in its atrium can make you appreciate its symmetrical and monochromatic design. Lucky you if a plane or bird gets in the frame.
experiences.name: Ping Shek Estate

experiences.introduction: Tucked near high-rise buildings is a little paradise with a pier amidst crashing waves—the Sai Wan Swimming Shed. On a crowded day, head up the steps of the swimming shed and take a wide-angle shot.
experiences.name: Sai Wan Swimming Shed

experiences.introduction: Natural daylight can make any photo look good, and you'll have plenty of this at Wai Yip Street Pedestrian Bridge. It has distinct white, blue, and pink interiors, perfect for a pastel backdrop!
experiences.name: Wai Yip Street Pedestrian Bridge

experiences.introduction: Ever since Korean actor Ji Chang-wook did a photoshoot at the mural in Graham Street, visitors have been flocking to this spot to take pictures. Don’t miss out on this bandwagon!
experiences.name: Graham Street

experiences.introduction: Who would have thought that China Hong Kong City can make a picturesque spot during sunset? The golden screen walls will bask your subject with a gentle glow—a literal golden hour shot.
experiences.name: China Hong Kong City

experiences.introduction: Xiqu Centre features a modern approach in its exterior design while depicting grandiosity in the interior. Established in 2019, this building is a world-class performing arts centre.
experiences.name: Xiqu Centre

experiences.introduction: The Mills is where you can take Insta-worthy shots while learning about Hong Kong’s rich industrial history. There’s an experiential retail area where you can meet new and established businesses.
experiences.name: The Mills

experiences.introduction: A vibrant green, Insta-worthy backdrop awaits you at Yuen Long Green Tunnel. A pedestrian subway linking Tai Kei Leng to Yuen Long, it’s lit with yellow light, giving off a surreal and warm effect.
experiences.name: Yuen Long Green Tunnel

collectionDetail.name: Crazy for Street Art!
collectionDetail.introduction: Hit the streets and check out these masterpieces!

experiences.introduction: Ever since Korean actor Ji Chang-wook did a photoshoot at the mural in Graham Street, visitors have been flocking to this spot to take pictures. Don’t miss out on this bandwagon!
experiences.name: Graham Street

experiences.introduction: Christian Storm’s two koi fish mural is a tranquil sight to behold in Shing Wong Street. Formerly plain and uninteresting, this concrete wall can now be a cool backdrop for your shots.
experiences.name: Shin Wong Street

experiences.introduction: The murals in Art Lane have revitalised the old buildings present here. These art-and-music-themed illustrations can make colourful backdrop for your next shots. Visit this place soon!
experiences.name: Art Lane

experiences.introduction: A mashup of Astroboy, Felix the Cat, and Pikachu awaits you at 2 Star Street, Wan Chai. Created by New York street artist Jerkface, this mural’s vivid colours can make a cartoonish backdrop.
experiences.name: Star Street

experiences.introduction: Stop, look, and think as you pass by the mural at 48 Elgin Street, Central depicting a rainy evening on a busy street. The bright and neon-like colours make it a relaxing sight to behold.
experiences.name: Elgin Street

experiences.introduction: The multicoloured Rainbow Thief on Man Fung building stands out amidst the plain structures around it. This lively mural can make a funky background for your shots.
experiences.name: Man Fung Building

experiences.introduction: Mysterious French artist Invader has graced Harbour City with his playful pixelated street paintings. Do the Invader Hunt Challenge and take shots of these lovely artworks around the city!
experiences.name: Harbour City

experiences.introduction: Want to see country leaders playing mahjong? You can find them at Sing Lei Mahjong Parlour’s signage. Snap a shot with this vibrant, neon-like caricature street art in the background.
experiences.name: Sing Lei Mahjong Parlour

experiences.introduction: Walk by the E Tat Factory Building and you will find a massive mural drawn on the building’s side depicting a dragon (or snake?) entangling a hand. Snap a shot for remembrance!
experiences.name: E Tat Factory Building

experiences.introduction: L'Epicerie Fine Art collaborates with local businesses where artists can put up their street art. Catch one of their works on the façade of La Cabane Wine Bistro!
experiences.name: L'Epicerie Fine HK

experiences.introduction: Foxglove proves that the best places are hidden in plain sight. This speakeasy presents itself as an umbrella shop on Duddell Street. Go towards the back of the boutique and find the entrance there.
experiences.name: Foxglove

experiences.introduction: Xiqu Centre features a modern approach in its exterior design while depicting grandiosity in the interior. Established in 2019, this building is a world-class performing arts centre.
experiences.name: Xiqu Centre

experiences.introduction: Having fun does not have to hurt. Go to Ryze Trampoline Park and try its trampolines, jumping boards, and foam pits. Bounce off the walls and jump all you want without fear of hurting yourself!
experiences.name: Ryze Trampoline Park

experiences.introduction: Choose your own adventure here at Superpark, a 45,-square foot facility for a variety of recreational activities and sports. It is divided into the Adventure Area, Game Arena, and Freestyle Hall.
experiences.name: Superpark
